{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930110201/0394.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER.\n(V. 8. Weather Bureau Forecast.)\nPair, with slowly rising temperature:\ntomorrow, fair and warmer.\nTemperatures\u2014Hlghaat, 48. at 4 p.m.\nyesterday; lowest, 37, at 4 a.m. yes\nterday.\nPull report on page 2.\nNo. 1,337 \u2014No.\nCONGRESS CONTROL\nSEEN AS LIKELY TO\nSTAY REPUBLICAN\nDemocratic Majority Regard\ned Possible, But Not Prob\nable Next Tuesday.\nDEPRESSION AND LIQUOR\nMOST DISCUSSED ISSUES\nI\nCains by Minority Party and Wets\nConceded in Most Political\nQuarters.\nComplete and interesting\nreports of the campaigns in\nthe States, with forecasts of\nTuesday\u2019s results gathered\nin The Star\u2019s Nation-wide\npolitical survey, will be found\nin Part 1, section C, pages 1\nto 9. of today\u2019s Star.\nBY G. GOULD LINCOLN.\nRepublican control of Congress Is\nthreatened in Tuesday's election, with\ndepression and prohibition the chief\ncontributing factors.\nDemocrats are due to make heavy\nInroads into big Republican majorities\nIn both House and Senate.\nWhile these Democratic galas are to\nbe large, there appears to be only a\npassibility, not a probability, that a\nclear majority will be obtained by the\nDemocrats in either House of Congress.\nOwing to discontment because of eco- J\nnomic conditions in the country, how\never. the swing to the Democrats may\nyet assume landslide proportions. If it\ndoes, possibility will become an accom\nplished fact. The Republican majority\nin the House will be wiped out. A\nDemocratic majority in the Senate is\nmore remote possibility than a Demo\ncratic majority in the House.\n4 Controlled Since 1918.\nControl of both houses of Congress\nhas rested with the Republicans since\nthe election of 1918, the midway point\nin the last presidential term of Presi\ndent Woodrow Wilson. In the present\nCongress, although the Republicans\nnominally have 17 more Senate scats\nthan the Democrats, a \u201ccoalition\u201d of\nRepublican insurgents and Democrats\nsought to prevent the adoption of ad\nministration measures. The huge lead\nof the Republicans in the House. 103,\nhowever, has made it possible for Presi- 1\ndent Hoover to have his way in major i\nIssues.\nThe election two days hence promises\nto be of far greater Import than the\nusual \u201coff year\u201d election, coming in the.\nmidst of the presidential term. Bound\nup in it are the probable political for\ntunes of leaders of both the major:\nparties. The election, too, is expected\nto give impetus to the drive to do away\nwith national prohibition as it now\nexists, or to throw a wet blanket on\nthe hopes of the anti-prohibitionists.\nElection of a Democratic House or;\nSenate, or both, would be regarded as j\na \u2022\u2018repudiation\u201d of the Hoover adminis\ntration. Certainly it would make the\nPresident\u2019s legislative program more i\n\u25a0iflicult of accomplishment than ever.\nIn the two remaining years of his term,;\nhowever. President Hoover, no matter j\nhat happens on Tuesday, may attain 1\n4 more commanding position, especially\nV economic conditions should improve.\nSoreness Counted Upon.\nThe extent of the protest against\nfcard times cannot be gauged with exact\nness. Democratic candidates for the\nHouse and Senate are expected to ben\nefit greatly by this protest vote. It is\ngi secret that they are counting on the j\nbareness of the voters to bring Demo-\neratic victory.\nCo-existent with the struggle between\nthe G. O. P. ahd the Democratic party\nfor control of Congress is the struggle\nbetween the wets and the drys, the j\nprohibitionists and the supporters of\nrepeal of the national dry laws.\nThe cause of both the Democrat* and\nthe wet* has been aided this year by\nthe business depression. In almost\nevery State and congressional district\nwhere a wet and dry fight exists this\nYear, the Democratic candidate is car\nrying the wet standard. A notable ex\nception to this rule is found, however,\nIn Montana, where Senator Thomas J.\nWalsh, Democrat and dry. is opposed by\nJudge Albert J. Galen. Republican and\n\u201cwet. Without the aid given by depres\nsion, the Democrats in these wet and\ndry struggles might lose and the wet\ncause lose with them. For example if\nIt were not for business depression and\nit* accompanying unemployment prob\nlem. Robert J. Bulkley. Democratic can\ndidate for Senator in Ohio, who has an\nnounced for repeal of the eighteenth\namendment, would stand no show for\nelection there. His victory will be hailed\nas a victory for the wet cause, however.\nDepression and the prohibition issue are\ngoing hand in hand to elect candidates\nfor office this year.\nWets to Make Gain*.\nThe anti-prohibitionMs are due to\nmake galas in both the House and Sen\nate. Already the wets have gained in\na number of districts where anti-prohi\nbition candidates have been nominated\nover drys. In other districts wet can\ndidates are expected to defeat their\ndrv opponents. But the drys will con\ntinue to have big majorities in both\nHou*e and Senate in the next Congress.\nThe Democrats have sought to make\nthe tariff, farm relief and waterpower\ntheir campaign issues against the Re\npublicans. The Republicans have ac\ncepted all these issues and have gone\nto the mat on them. They may affect\nsome vote*. But in the main the great\ndetermining issue* will be those of hard\nContinued on Page 2. Column 2.)\nBANDITS MAKE WATCHMAN RING\nALARM, RESULTING IN CAPTURE\nPolice Cars Arrive When Seventh Box Proves Emergency\nRather Than Routine Box.\nBr the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, November 1. \u2014The lucky\nseventh was John Rusyel\u2019s inning, to\nthe deep humiliation ot five robbers\nwhom he \"outnumbered\u201d today.\nRusyel was night watching at a\ncleaning establishment when the quin\ntet surrounded him with a battery of\npistils.\n\"I have.\u201d the watchman warned\nthem, \u201cseven alarm boxes to puli in\nthree minutes.\u201d\n*>l Entered a* second rlass matter\npost office. Washington. D. C.\nIssues of the Campaign\nRepublicans Say Foes\nHave Stood on Tariff\nRepeal Alone.\nThe following statements, summarizing the issues presented to the\nvoters for decision in the general elections Tuesday, were prepared for\nThe Star by the Republican and Democratic National headquarters.\nBY ROBERT H. LUCAS.\nExecutive Director. Republican National\nCommittee.\nOn the eve of election there Is but\none real issue advocated by the Demo\ncratic party\u2014repeal of the tariff\u2014and\nthat has but recently been injected into\nRobert H. Loras.\nwhich so many of his party leaders in\nthe Senate worked and voted and to j\nhave the repeal \"without hearings or\nother ceremony.\u201d\nAs a fake issue the Democratic party\nj (Continued on Page 4. Column 2.) I\nVARGAS WILL TAKE\nOFFICE ON MONDAY\nBrazilian Revolutionary Chief\nAnnounces Financial\nReform Program.\nBy the Associated Press.\nRIO DE JANEIRO, November I.\nDr. Getulio Varga*, commander in chief\nof Brazil's successful revolutionists, an\nnounced this evening that he would\ntake office as provisional President of\nthe country on Monday afternoon, No\nvember 3.\nHis first official act will be to dis\nsolve Congress. He said that, owing to\nthe present political situation in the\ncountry, he would assume the presi\ndency \u201cwith discretionary power.\"\nHis announcement followed upon con\nsultations with the northern insurgent\nmilitary leader. Capt. Juarez Tavora,\nand officers of the military junta in the j 1\ncapital. The junta will probably be\nabolished within 48 hours.\nMore rebel troops reached Rio to-\nday from Minas Geraes, Sao Paulo and\ni Rio Grande Do Sul. The police here\nhave been very active against Com\nmunists. who are charged with being\nresponsible for the police revolt and\nj street fighting on October 27,\nIt was understood tonight that all\nbanks would resume exchange opera\ntions on Monday. A rate for the\nj milreis lower than the 9 3 to the dol\ni lar was forecast. This figure has been\nthe official quotation at the Banco do\n1 Brasil for the past two weeks.\nFinancial reform, comprising a vast\neconomic program, is one of the prin\ncipal planks in Dr. Vargas\u2019 platform as\nprovisional President of Brazil.\nOther Principles Announced.\nI Other principles for which the Var-\ngas administration will stand were an-\nI nounced as follows:\nSimplification of administrative pro\ncesses and war on political parasitism.:\nReduction of administrative expenses.\nSimplification of legal procedure.\nHonest elections.\nAdvancement of public instruction.\nConstitutional reforms relative to\njudicial and electoral procedure.\nReformation of the powers and re\nsponsibilities of the legislative and\nexecutive branches.\nIt also was said that Dr. Osvaldo\nAranha, who had much to do with\ncarrying on the revolution, probably\nwould be minister of Interior and jus\ntice in the new cabinet. Thus the gov\nernment will be dominated by leaders\nfrom Rio Grande do Sul, the southern\nmost state in which the revolt was bom\n_Triago Wurth, press representative\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 6.j\nWIFE OF NEWSPAPER MAN\nTHROWN FROM HORSE\nMr*. R. S. Pickens Treated at\nGeorgetown Hospital for Injuries\nAbout Head.\nj Thrown from her horse while riding\non the campus of American University\nyesterday afternoon, Mrs. R. S Pickens.\n300i> Forty-fifth street, well known in\nWashington press circles and wife of\nRobert S Pickens, newspaperman, was\npainfully but not seriously injured\nMrs. Pickens is in Georgetown Uni\nversity Hospital suffering from injuries\nabout the head, bruises and shock.\nAccording to Mr. Pickens, he and his\nW'ife were out for a canter when, for\nsome reason he has not discovered,\nhis wife's mount became frightened and\nI bolted. Mis. Pickens sought vainly to\ncheck the horse but failed, and was\nthrown heavily to the ground, striking\non her head.\nPickens rode up. picked up his wife,\ncarried her to Nebraska avenue, where\nI he obtained an automobile and rushed\nher to Georgetown University Hospital\n\u201cGood.\u201d they said. \"Well see that\nyou pull them all.\u201d\ni They strolled about the plant to\ni gether. Rusyel pulled six boxes.\n\u201cAh. l.a! That's only six.\u201d his cap\ni tors smiled \"Where's No. 7? Come\non, pull It!\u201d\nHe did. In a moment the crescendo\nof police car sirens brought chills to\nl five spines\ni The robbers were captured. Box No.\nf was the emergency alarm.\n\u00a9he iumXau J\u00a7k\u00a3\nWITH DAILY EVENING EDITION\nDemocrats to Rest Their\nCase on Success or\nFailure of Hoover.\n\ni BY CHARLES MICHELSON.\nPublicity Director. Democratic National\nCommitter.\nIssues of the political campaign that\nculminates in Tuesday s election are all\nembraced in the general question of\nwhether the Hoover administration has\nthe campaign. Be\nfore it emerged\nfrom the Demo\ncratic smoke screen\nwith sound accom\npanim en t. the\nDemocratic party\nhad sponsored\nnothing but attacks\nupon the President\nand the admini\nstration.\nJames M. Cox in i\na Nation- wide\nradio address made\nrepeal of the tariff j\nan issue. He prom-\ni-ed to strike from j\nthe statute books\nthe Hawlev-Smoot\ntariff, the bill for I\nbeen a success or a\nfailure. In other\nwords has the\ncountry sustained\nat the hands of the\npresent administra\ntion such a direc\ntion of public af\nfairs as was prom\nised when Mr.\nHoover asked the\nsuffrage of the\nAmerican people?\nI If he was elected:\njif his party was\nj confirmed in its\nstewardship of the\nI Government cer\nj tain things were\nj guaranteed the\npeople of this\ncountry.\nChief of these was prosperity. The\npresidential candidate of that cam\npaign advised the electorate that a\ncontinuance of national good times de-\nI (Continued on Page 4, Column 3.)\nBO X HOPS TODAY\nON TRIP TO 0. Si\nGreat Flying Boat Likely to;\nIgnore Weather on Amster\ndam Flight.\nBy the Associated Press.\nALTENRHEIN. Switzerland, Novem\nber I.\u2014Weather reports from the north,\nalong the course over which the gr at j\nflying boat DO-X is to fly tomorrow on\nthe first leg of her flight across the\nocean to America, were unfavorable to\nnight, but arc not expected to delay the\nairship's departure.\nComdr. Friedrich Christiansen was\nnot gloomy at the prospect.\nStart Set for 8 A.M.\n\u201cWe will be off shortly after 8 o\u2019clock\nin the morning,\u201d he said.\nAll the mechanics and other members\nof the crew were ordered to be aboard\nthe airship by 7:30 a.m.\nHer fuel tanks were full and engineers\nhad made the last adjustments to her\ninstruments in final preparations for\na start to Amsterdam at 8 o\u2019clock\n(3 a.m. Eastern standard time).\nSelect Tentative Route.\nComdr. Christiansen said he planned j\nto head his ship into the west, follow\ning the Rhine until it winds into Hol\nland. but his exact route will be de\ntermined by the weather he encounters\nand by how much daylight is left after\nthe take-off.\nIf the start takes place promptly at\n8 o'clock, the pilot should sight Schill\ningwoude, th\" Dutch naval airport out\nside Amsterdam, between 1 and 2\no\u2019clock in the afternoon.\n35 Hours Over Ocean.\nThe transatlantic cruise is expected\nto consume about 35 hours of actual\nflying time, but th\u00b0 amount of time for\nlayovers at the various scheduled stops\nen route depends on the weather and\nother contingencies. It Is not unlikely\nthat the DO-X may take a we?k oi\nmore to reach New York from Lisbon\nTen hours is the estimated flying\ni time from Lisbon to the Azores and\nthere probably w r ill be a one-dav lay\nover th'T* bpfore the start of a 12-hour\nleg to a tank ship which will be waiting\nabout 700 miles southwest of Bermuda.\nIt will be only a brief stay at the\ntanker before the 6-hour hop to Ber\nmuda begins. At least one day will be\nsp-nt on th\" island, and perhaps several\ndays, before the final 7-hour stretch\nto New York begins.\nKIDNAPERS SEIZE\nRICH REALTY MAN\nRansom of SIO,OOO Is Asked of\nWife After Abduction by\nFour Bogus \u201cAgents.\nBy the Associated Press.\nDETROIT. November I.\u2014Relatives of\nCharles Kaier, 42. wealthy retired real\nestate dealer, reported to police tonight\nthat Kaier was kidnapad Thursday\nnight by four men who have demanded\nSIO,OOO ransom.\nPolice said the report was made to\nthem after Mrs. Kaier had taken $2,000 j\nfrom a bank to a hotel where she was\nto meet the kidnapers.\nThe abductors, police were informed,\ndid not keep the engagement and Mrs.\nKaier collapsed.\nThe report to the authorities said\nS that fsur men who represented them\ni selves as 'Federal agents\" visited the\nj Kaier home Thursday night and told I\nI him he was \"wanted at headquarters.\" I\nHe accompanied them, and later the i\nransom demands were made, police\ni said.\nThe police did not learn Immediately\nwhat negotiations led to today's unkept\nj rendezvous.\nJ Detective Sergt.. Reuben Haynes, who\nj was working on the case, said that Mrs.\nKaier was in a highly nervous condi\ntlon and could not be interviewed to\nnight.\nHaynes said the bogus \"Federal\nagents\" used *hc name of the district\nattorney in their conversation with\nKaier.\nMan, 80, Seeks Divorce.\nBATON ROUGE. La, November 1\n<A>). \u2014Sambola Jones, B 0 years old. and\nI former United States Minister to Hon\ni! duras, has filed suit for divorce from\nI Mrs. Julia D. Jones, aged 28. on the\nj grounds of desertion They were mar\nried in Honduras when Mrs. Jones\nwas If.\nWASHINGTON, l). C\\, SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 2, 1930-134 PAGES.\nCharles Mlchclson.\nS. INTERVENTION\nMAY SOLVE NAVAL\nPACT DIFFICULTIES\nOffers Through Gibson to End\nDangerous Franco-ltalian\nRivalry.\nI MAY ENTER CONSULTATIVE\nPLAN IN PEACE INTEREST\n\u2019\u2019Parity\u201d Is Chief Difficulty\u2014Four-\nParty Treaty Seen as Pos\nsibility.\nBY PAUL SCOTT MOWRER.\nBy Radio to The Star.\nPARIS, France. November I.\u2014The\nUnited States is making an erergetic\neleventh-hour intervention for Euro\npean peace and world disarmament. It\nhas offered, through Hugh S. Gibson,\nAmbassador to Belgium, its good offices\nJto bring a happy conclusion to the\nj long-standing and dangerous Franco\nItalian naval rivalry.\nWhere Great Britain in seven months\nof almost continuous efforts has failed,\nour diplomacy still courageously hopes\nto succeed. Although the difficulties\nare, if anything, greater than ever,\nthese hopes seem not wholly unwar\nranted. Great Britain Is supporting\nus, but the initiative continues in our\nj hands.\nEvents are moving fast, and already\nvast possibilities are mooted. One of\nthese is a short-term agreement on\nfigures, leaving the parity issue to be\nI settled later. Another, which has been\nI mentioned particularly in Washington\nI dispatches to the London press. Is that\nin case general disarmament proves\npractical the United States may be\nwilling to enter a consultative paot\nwith ether leading powers in the inter\nests of world peace.\nMay Extendi Locarno Term*.\nBoth of these proposals came up\nduring the London Naval Conference\nand fell through for one reason or an\nother. Another possibility is a four\nparty treaty omitting Italy. It is said\nthat Great Britain may be willing to\ngrant an extension of the terms of the\nLocarno pact to the North Sea area,\nthus insurance France and incidentally\nGermany against naval attack in this\nregion and supposedly enabling a cor\nresponding reduction in the French\nfigures.\nAll three of these suggestions are be\nlieved to contain interesting potential\nities. Is it worth noting that this is\nthe third step taken by the United\nStates in the last few weeks in the\nsupposed direction of European peace,\nfollowing the recent international ten\nsion and disarray?\nFirst was the $125,000,000 credit by\nAmerican banks to Germany, which,\nit is conceded, has done more than\nanything else to strengthen the presen:\nGerman government against the as\nsaults of the Hitlerites and the Com\nmunists.\nSecond was the formal refusal of\nPresident Herbert Hoover and Secre\ntary of State Henry L. Stimson to en\ncourage the Germans In the idea of a\nmoratorium or revision of the Young\nplan or war debts in any near future.\nOur viewpoint seems to be that such\na move in present circumstances would\nmerely be an additional cause of inter\nnational disturbance and therefore\nhighly inopportune.\nOur friendlv intervention in the\nFranco-ltalian difficulties, is said to be\ndue pattly to the fact that Great Brit\nain has informed us that it will be\nobliged to Invoke the escape clause of\nthe London treaty and build beyond\nthe treaty figures if France and Italy\nkeep on building and partly to the ad\nministration\u2019s desire to achieve some\nstriking success in foreign policy, but\nmainly to Mr. Hoover s firm belief that\nthe furtherance of peace through dis\narmament will be the surest way to\nbring back better economic conditions\nto a sorely tried world.\nSecrecy Being Observed.\nAlthough the strictest secrecy Is being j\nobserved in the negotiations, Ambas- j\nsador Gibson seems to have seen Pre\ni mier Andre Tardieu of France and\nPhilippe Bcrthelot, general secretary of\nthe French foreign office, on Monday\nI and Tuesday and then left quietly for\ni Rome. On Wednesday the British Am\nbassador seems to have seen M. Berthe\nlot. On Thursday Mr. Gibson, in Rome,\nsaw Foreign Minister Dino Grand!, and\ni Continued on Page 2, Column 1.)\nI TODAY\u2019S STAR\nPART ONE\u20143B PAGES.\nGeneral News \u2014Loral, National and\nForeign.\nSchools and Colleges\u2014Page B-4.\nStar's Nation-wide Political Survey-\nPages C-l to C-9.\nSerial Story. \u201cThe Scarab Murder\nCase\u201d\u2014 Page C-12.\nD. A R. Activities\u2014 Page C-12.\nY W C. A. Notes \u2014Page C-12.\nOrganized Reserves\u2014Page C-12.\nPART TWO\u2014B PAGES.\nEditorials and Editoriil Features.\nPirrent-Teacher Activities \u2014Page 5.\nAt Communi\u2019y Centers- Page 5.\nPART THREE\u2014I 6 PAGES.\nSociety Section.\nPART FOl R\u2014l 2 PAGES.\nAmusement Section\u2014Theater. Screen\n1 and Music.\nIn the Motor World\u2014Page 5.\nAviation \u2014Page 7.\nFraternities \u2014Page 8\nDistrict of Columbia Naval Reserve\nPage 8.\nNews of the Clubs\u2014Page 9.\nArmy and Navy News\u2014Page 9.\ni Veterans of the Great War Page 9.\nRadio\u2014Page 10.\nPART FIVE\u20146 PAGES.\nSports Section.\nPART SIX\u2014I 2 PAGES.\nFinancial News and Classified Adver\ntising.\nThe Home Gardener\u2014 Page 12.\nW C T. U. Notes \u2014Page 12.\nDistrict National Guard\u2014Page 12.\nSpanish War Veterans\u2014 Page 12.\nMarine Corps Notes\u2014 Page 12.\nPART SEVEN\u2014 24 PAGES.\nMagazine Section.\nNotes of Art and Artists\u2014 Page 18\nReviews of the New Books Page 19.\nCross-word Puzzle\u2014Page 22.\nGRAPHIC SECTION \u20141* PAGES.\nWorld Events in Pictures.\nCOLOR SECTION\u2014B PAGES.\nMoon Mullins; Mutt and Jeff: Mr. and\nMrs.; Little Orphan Annie; Brutus;\nthe Smythes; Somebody* Stenos;\nHighlights of History.\nJ\nIX NEBRASKA AS XOVKMBER 4th NEARS!\nCUE INCREASES\nTHROUGHOUT U. S.\nMurder Takes Spurt Along\nWith Other Offenses in\nLast Nine Months.\nBY REX COLLIER.\nGangsters\u2019 guns are speaking with\nmore regularity and greater effective\nness.\nTheir deadly voices have poured into\nUncle Sam's ear a sordid story of crime\nrampant and on the increase during the\nfirst three-quarters of the current year,\naccording to a Nation-wide inquiry con\nducted under the direction of J. Edgar\nHoover, head of the United States Bu\nreau of Investigation.\nA chart for the period from January I\nthrough September, just published by\nDirector Hoover in the second monthly\nreport of hts survey, discloses a steadily\nmounting trend of crime in general dur\ning the nine months, with murder\nsharply in the ascendancy.\nUpward Trend Lately.\nThe total of all \u2018\u2018offenses known to\npolice,\u201d officially classified as \"murder\nand non-negligent manslaughter, man\nslaughter by negligence, rape, robbery,\naggravated assault, burglary (breaking\nor entering), larceny and automobile\ntheft,\u201d dropped slightly last February,\nrose rapidly in March, fell off again in\nApril and May and then began a grad\nual upward curve that has had no in\nterruption since the Spring.\nThe trail of murder descended slight\nly in February, shot skyward abruptly\nin March, wavered and declined in April\nand May and ever since has been climb\ning to new peaks for the year. There j\nwas no noticeable change in the mur\ni der situation during August and Sep\ntember, after a steady upgrade during\nthe Summer.\nAt the outset of the year murderers\nwere claiming an average of three vic\ntims a day. In September the average\ni was more nearly five a day.\nAverage Four Killed.\n\u201cNegligent manslaughter,\u201d under\nwhich the Government classifies all I\nhomicides not first or second degree 1\nmurder, shewed an aggregate decline\nduring the nine months. An average\ni of four persons were killed each day by\nnegligence in January, while \"three and\na half\u201d persons was the average last\nmonth.\nPetty larceny (theft of under SSO,\naccording to official classifications) has\nbeen on the upgrade since February, j\nwhen a slight falling off from January\nwas apparent.\nLarceny of sums over SSO declined in j\nthe Spring, rase again during the Sum- I\nmer and has slumped a few degrees\nduring August and September.\nAn encouraging sign, viewing the\nperiod as a whole, is a net decrease in 1\nthe average daily number of robberies, i\nMore than 50 hold-ups a day were j\nrecorded in January, the average drop-\nping to a low mark of a little above\n30 a day in May and then advancing\nagain to more than 40 last month.\nReport on Burglaries.\nBurglaries do not seem to vary much.\nThe average has remained under 150\na day.\n\"Aggravated assault\u201d has shown a\ntendency to climb from near 20 a day\nto almost 30 a day.\nA study of the figures discloses that\nthe most frequent offense is minor\nlarceny, the cases of which embrace\nabout one-third of the total of all\ncrimes reported. A typical distribu\ntion of the offense? is shown in the\nSeptember returns, of which 33.9 per\ncent are reports of larcefiies under SSO,\n26 per cent automobile thefts. 19 7 per\ncent burglaries. 9 1 per cent larcenies\nover SSO, 5.4 per cent robberies, 4.5\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 3\nGREEN WARNS WORKERS\nTO AVOID HOOVER DAM\nPlans for Construction Declared\nInsufficiently Advanced Now to\nAfford Many Jobs.\nBy the Associated Press.\nWilliam Green, president of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor, yester\nday advised workers to stay away from\nHoover Dam, asserting there was no\nimmediate prospect of employment\nthere.\nAfter receiving what he termed a de\ntailed report on the project, the labor\nleader said \u201cit will be nearly a year\nbefore a contract can be let for con\nstruction.\u201d The report, from an un\nnamed source, said bids for construc\ntion of the division tunnel and dam\nproper probably would not be called\nbefore next July.\nThe report said in part: \u201cIt is neces-\nI sary to emphasize this in order to cor\nj rect the general impression which seems\nto prevail that a large construction\nforce ia to be organised at once.\u201d\nSports Highlights\nAn unusual number of tie\ngames resulted from activities on\nthe gridirons of the Nation yts\nterday. At least 10 were recorded\nand a majority were scoreless,\nthese including the Yale-Dart\nmeuth, Princeton-Chicago, Ne\nbraska-Pitt, Florida-Georgia, Wis\nconsin-Ohio State, V. P. 1.-Wash\nington and Lee and Gallaudet-\nMedicai Field service team games.\nOther battles resulting in draws\nwere those between Syracuse and\nBrown at 16-all, Georgia Tech\nand North Carolina, 6-6. and\nHarvard vs. William and Mary,\n13-13.\nThe feat of the Indians from\nWilliamsburg in holding the\nstrong Crimson array cn even\nterms at Cambridge was one of\nthe upsets of the day, others\nbeing the 21-to-6 smearing Penn\nhanded the strong Kansas Uni\nversity outfit, the 27-to-7 trounc\ning Texas inflicted on Southern\nMethodist U. and New York Uni\nversity's 20-to-7 victory over j\nCarnegie Tech.\nOs the local varsity elevens,\nMaryland, with a 14-6 verdict,\nwas the cnly winner, as New\nRiver State beat Catholic Uni\nversity. 20-6; St. John's swamped\nAmerican U\u201e 59-6, and Western\nMaryland blanked the Marines.\n20-0. and Virginia State nosed\nout Howard University, 16-13.\nNotre Dame romped on toward\nthe mythical national champion\nship by submerging Indiana. 27-0;\nAlabama drove another spike in\nthe Southern Conference crown\nby walloping Kentucky, 19-0, and\nNorthwestern furthered its ambi\ntion to win the Big Ten title by\ntaking Minnesota, 27-6. Army\nand Navy had an easy time of it,\ndefeating North Dakota and West\nVirginia Wesleyan, 33-6 and 37-\n14, respectively.\nDetails of these and other\ngames will be found in the sports\nsection.\nCHICAGO MAYOR\u2019S\nCONDITION CRITICAL\n\nThompson Awakens From\nHis Operation to Ask\nAbout Politics.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, November 1 .\u2014Physicians\nattending Mayor William Hale Thomp\nson issued the following statement at\n6:30 o\u2019clock tonight:\n\u201cThe mayor\u2019s condition remains criti\ncal. His temperature and pulse are as\nwe would expect under the circum-\nI stances. \u00bbHe is resting comfortably.\u201d\nWhen Mayor Thompson awoke after\nthe operation he was in jovial mood\nand his thoughts reverted to the politi\nj cal meeting he was to have addressed\nin a downtown theater yesterday in op\nposition to Ruth Hanna McCormick,\ni Republican nominee for the United\nStates Senate. His speech was read\nby a member of his cabinet.\nDr. Milton M. Portis said he asked to\nsee the papers.\n\u201cI want to read what the boys have\nbeen writing about me,\u201d Dr. Portis\nquoted him.\nThe paper? were refused him, but Dr.\nPortis told him to rest assured \"the\nnewspaper boys have handled things\nvery nicely.\"\nLater he asked his friend. Robert M.\nPerbohner. if anv of the papers printed\nthe speech. Told they did not, he\nsmiled. Perbohner said, and declared\n\"I didn't think they would.\u201d\nThe speech was a vitriolic attack\nI upon the Chicago Tribune and its pres\nent and past editors.\nCANNON AGAIN SUFFERS\nSPREAD OF INFECTION\nCondition of Bishop at Hospital\nDescribed as Serious, But\nNot Critical.\nBy the Associated Press.\nDr. R. Lyman Sexton, who has been\nattending Bishop James Cannon, jr\u201e of\nthe Methodist Episcopal Church South,\nsaid early this morning the arthritis in\nfection suffered by the churchman had\nbegun spreading again and now has\nreached above the right knee.\nBishop Cannon's condition was de\nscribed as \u201cserious but not critical.\u201d Dr.\nSexton said the infection appeared to\nhave been checked during the day but\nthat a relapse had caused it to advance\nto joints not hitherto affected.\nThe churchman entered the hospital\nlast week tor treatment.\nt\nFIVE CENTS\nIN WASHINGTON AND SUBURBS\nHAVENNER DEFEATS\ni STENGLE, II TO 33\nHis Third Successive Term as\nPresident Is Won on\nFirst Ballot.\nDr. George C. Havenner vu re\nelected president of the Federation of\nCitizens' Associations last night for the\nthird successive term, decisively de\nfeating his only opponent, Charles I.\nStengle, by a vote of 77 to 33.\nDr. Havenner's re-election came on\nthe first ballot, and he swept into\noffice the same three men who have\nserved with him during his first two\nterms as head of the federation \u2014B. A.\nBowles, vice president; David Babp,\nrecording secretary, and A. H. Gregory,\ntreasurer.\n112 Delegate* Attend.\nThe election marked the close of\nan Intensive campaign between Dr.\nHavenner and Stengle and was par\nticipated in by 112 delegates, the\nlargest number ever to attend a meet\ning of the federation. Os the 112 votes\ncast two of them went to William McK.\nClayton, first president of the federa\ntion and now chairman of Its Important\nCommittee on Public Utilities, who was\nnot a candidate and was not nomi\nnated.\nStengle\u2019s defeat did not come as a\nsurprise, although his supporters had\npredicted his victory. But Dr. Haven\nner announced on the eve of the elec\nj tion that he would be re-elected by a\nsubstantial majority, and said he\ncounted on 70 votes, just 7 less than\nhe actually received.\nDr. Havenner was nominated by\nGeorge R. Wales, who extolled the fed\neration's record of achievements during\nthe first two years of his administration.\nThe seconding speeches were' made by\nFred A. Emery and MaJ. A. M. Hol\ncombe\nStengle\u2019* Work Praised.\nHenry I. Quinn, who headed Stengle\u2019s\nCampaign Committee nominated him,\nand the seconding speeches came from\nE. M. Richardson and W. J. Neale.\nQuinn urged the election of Stengle as\na reward for his five years of service to\norganized citizenship of the District,\nas delegate to the federation from the\nPetworth Citizens\u2019 Association and also\nas a member of the Citizens\u2019 Advisory\nCouncil for three terms.\nBowles also had one opponent in the\ncontest for the federation's vice presi\ndency Miss Etta Taggart, the first\nwoman ever elected by the federation to\nthe Advisory Council. Bowles defeated\nher on the first- ballot by a vote of 72\nto 32._ One vote each also was cast for\ntContinued on Page 2, Column 6.)\nHOOVERS MARK BALLOTS\nAbsentee Votes Are Dispatched to\nCalifornia by Airmail.\nThree days ahead of time, President\nand Mrs. Hoover marked their ballots\nyesterday for the general elections.\nVoting on absentee ballots forwarded\nfrom Palo Alto, Calif., the White House\noccupants made their choice and then\nImmediately dispatched their votes by\nairmail back to California. They are\nexpected to reach the proper polls by\nTuesday easily.\nThe privacy of the ballot was respect\ned even for the President, and no one\nasked him if he had expressed his\npreference for the straight Republican\nticket.\nI BROTHER OF FIRE AUTO VICTIM\nINJURED IN SIMILAR ACCIDENT\nMarlboro Jinx at Wheel Saturdays, Chief McCormick\nEscaping Injury Second Time.\nA Jinx rides at the wheel with Chief\nW. W. McCormick of the Marlboro Fire\nDepartment on Saturdays, it seems,\nwith painful effect on the members of\nthe kerr family in Marlboro.\nThus far on successive Saturday aft\nernoons\u2014yesterday afternoon and Sat\nurday of last week\u2014one man has been\nkilled and two members of the Kerr\nfamily injured in automobile accidents\nwhen McCormick was at the wheel. In\nboth accidents McCormick has escaped\nunscathed.\nYesterday afternoon it was Charles\nKerr whp was hurt when McCormick\u2019s\nmachine, on the way to Casualty Hos\npital, where he and Kerr weit to visit\nWesley Kerr, Injured last\nwhile riding with McCormick, Vwe c in\nj a collision with a machine drfWkn by\nFrank R. Ferguson of Meadows, ad.\n\u201cFrom Press to Homo\nWithin the Hour* 9\nThe Star Is delivered every evening and\nSunday morning to Washington homes by\nThe Star's exclusive carrier service. Phone\nNational 5000 to start immediate delivery.\nMeans Associated Press.\nWOODS URGES ALL\nWHO CAN TO BUY\nAS AID TO JOBLESS\nMany Suggestions Received\nby Committee as Balm\nfor Unemployed.\nCHAIRMAN ASKS STUDY\nOF CINCINNATI FIRM PLAN\nSenator George Fears Work Plan\nby Government Will Start\nToo Late.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNew balms for the aches of unem\nployment were proposed yesterday to\nthe President's Emergency Committee\nas a word of advice came from ltd\nchairman for prospective purchasers.\nScores cf communications poured Into\nthe mail box of the committee telling\nof successful efforts by civic and welfare\norganizations and Government bodies to\nprovide work.\nAt the same time Col. Arthur Woods,\nchairman of the committee, admonished\ni these without Income or savings to buy\nwisely, but encouraged those who could\nafford to make purchases without en\ndangering their finances to do so. Not\nonly would purchases now stimulate in\ndustry and employment, he said, but\nthey would constitute wise economy in\nview of the generally low prices.\nCites Cincinnati Company.\nThe chairman recommended to in\ndustry a study of the plan adopted by\nProcter Si Gamble of Cincinnati to keep\nits 10,000 workers in plants in eight\nAmerican and Canadian cities at work\nthe year round without reduction to\nsalaries. The company advised him to\nday its monthly pay roll amounted to\n$1,000,000, and assured 50,000 men,\nwomen and children of a comfortable\nliving through the Wint?r.\nMeanwhile the War Department an\nnounced projects costing $3,074,721 had\nbeen put under way, and the Interior\nDepartment said it would ask for bids\nfor contracts totaling $3,000,000 Novem\nber 15 on the Hoover Dam project on\nthe Colorado River in order to give em\nployment.\nRepresentative Celler, Democrat, New\nYork, urged that the Navy be built\nup to the maximum strength allowed\nunder the London naval treaty, m an\nemployment measure.\nGeorge Say* It** \"Hokum.\"\nSenator George, Democrat. Georgia,\nsaid yesterday there was a \"good deal\nof hokum in the trumpet blasts about\nunemployment that the administration\nis letting loose just before the election.\"\nGeorge said he wanted to co-operate\nwith any program to relieve unemploy\nment and was heartily in favor of\nany move to aid the pepol* out of\nwork, but that he \"was afraid the fan\nfare would lead to false impressions\nthat would in turn lead to disappoint\nment.\u201d\n\"The truth of the business.\" ha\nadded, \"is that the administration has\nbeen slow in starting its building pro\ngram. There has been unreasonable\ndelay in letting contracts and other\nsnail-like moves in a time that called\nfor unhampered rapidity. The Winter\nwill be almost over before the program\nabout which we hear so much can\ngive any real relief, for the Treasury\u2019s\nmethods will continue, I'm afraid,\nbe slow, despite the announcements,\u201d\nGeorge said the administration had\naided in accentuating the depression\nby not lending its support at the last\nsession to the Wagner bills to relieve\nunemployment. These contemplated a\nplanned program of public building,\nwith acceleration during times of de\npression and a fund to carry on the\nwork.\nThe Democratic Senator added he\nhad sponsored a joint resolution at the\nlast session which urged expedition of\nthe public building program.\n\"The resolution passed.\" he said, \"but\nthe expediting has yet to be done.\u201d\nMISSING BOAT SOUGHT\nCoast Guard Cutter Searches Lake\nSuperior for Grain Carrier.\nSAULT STE. MARIE. Mich.. Novem\nber 1 \u2014The big Coast Guard cutter,\nSeminole, this afternoon began a thor\nough-going search of Lake Superior\nbetween the American mainland and\nMichipicoten Island In an effort to lo\ncate the Canadian grain-carrier. Ash\nbay. overdue here since Wednesday.\nThe Ashbay, with a crew of 25 men,\nleft Port William at 7 p.m. Tuesday\n1 headed for Sault Ste. Marie. On the\nnext night the light keeper on Michipi\ncoten Lsland reported seeing a steamer\nin distress. A search failed to reveal\ni any boat, and it was only after it was\ndiscovered that the Ashbay was- long\noverdue that, the Coast Guard accepted\nthe report from the island as probably\nI correct.\n\nQuake Felt in New York.\nMALONE, N. Y\u201e November 1 UP).\u2014\nA slight earthquake shook Malone and\nvicinity at 9:40 o\u2019clock tonight. No\ndamage was reported. The tremors\ni were felt throughout a considerable\narea.\nWesley Kerr. Charles' brother, was\nhurt while riding on the Marlboro fire\nengine Saturday afternoon a week ago.\nMcCormick was driving it when it\nturned over trying to pass another ma\nchine on a gravel road near Ritchie,\nMd. In that accident B. Wesley Cran\nford, a captain in the Marlboro Fire\nDepartment, was killed, but McCormick\ncame through unhurt. A coroner\u2019s jury\nheld the accident was unavoidable.\nYesterday afternoon's accident oc\ncurred on the Marlboro pike near For\nestvllle. Charles Kerr was cut by fly\ning glass and treated by Dr. Paul C.\nVan Natta. Ferguson, the driver of\nthe other machine, was arrested\nSheriff Charles S. Early, who happened\nby. on charges of driving while drunk\nand failing to obey a stop sign. He\nwas released in 11.000 bond for ap\npearance in Police Court at Pbreat villa.\na\nTEN CENTS\nELSEWHKRK","height":"25266","width":"19692"}}
